data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8.

**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would be to replace raw threads with `Task.WhenAll` and support `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));
    await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
}

private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    Thread.Sleep(100); // or await Task.Delay(100, ct)
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}
```

This is a modernization improvement, not a required migration fix.
